firebase-ai.message:
[AI] Add support for on-device / cloud hybrid inference (#7739)

Refactors the generative model instantiation logic to support both
in-cloud and on-device backends. This change introduces the
`OnDeviceConfig` and `InferenceMode` types to the public API surface
under the `@PublicPreviewAPI` experimental annotation.

Backwards compatibility for existing cloud-only callers is maintained.

firebase-ai.author: Rodrigo Lazo
firebase-ai.message:
[AI] Standardize tool handling and function call limits (#7740)

Changed `tools` parameters and properties across `GenerativeModel`,
`LiveGenerativeModel`, and `FirebaseAI` from nullable `List<Tool>?` to
non-nullable `List<Tool>` with a default `emptyList()`. This simplifies
tool access and removes redundant null checks.

Introduced `requestOptions` as a direct property in `GenerativeModel` to
provide consistent access to request-specific settings. The
`autoFunctionCallingTurnLimit` in `Chat` now directly accesses
`model.requestOptions.autoFunctionCallingTurnLimit`, replacing the
`getTurnLimit()` method. The `getTurnLimit()` method was subsequently
removed from `GenerativeModel` and `APIController`.

Refactored `GenerativeModel` to use a consistent `List<Content>` input
for its core `generateContent`, `generateContentStream`,

- Renames `constructRequest` to `buildGenerateContentRequest` for better
readability

firebase-ai.author: Ros√°rio P. Fernandes
firebase-ai.message:
add @JvmOverloads for Tool.urlContext() and Tool.googleSearch() (#7695)

In their current state, when called from Java, these functions require
at least one argument:

```java
Tool urlContext = Tool.urlContext(new UrlContext());
Tool googleSearch = Tool.googleSearch(new GoogleSearch()));
```

while their Kotlin counterpart can be called with no arguments:

```kotlin
val urlContext = Tool.urlContext()
val googleSearch = Tool.googleSearch()
```

This commit should add `@JvmOverloads` so that the compiler creates the
respective no argument methods to be used in Java.

firebase-ai.author: Rodrigo Lazo
firebase-ai.message:
[AI] Don't end connection early when receiving GoAway (#7688)

Instead of finishing the session when the go away message is received,
keeping it open leaves more room for developers to implement different
strategies in their callback method. Additionally, it preserves the
current behaviour.

firebase-ai.author: YooJun Hong
firebase-ai.message:
[AI] Fix crash caused by unhandled goAway server message in LiveSession (#7649)

## Description

Fixes #7648

This PR adds support for the `goAway` server message type in LiveSession
to prevent crashes when the server initiates a disconnect. Previously,
when the server sent a `goAway` message, the app would crash with a
`SerializationException` because the message type was not recognized by
`LiveServerMessageSerializer`.

## Changes

### 1. Add LiveServerGoAway message type

- Added `LiveServerGoAway` class to represent server-initiated
disconnection
- Includes `timeLeft: Duration?` field from parsed protobuf format
string (e.g., "57s", "1.5s")
- Registered `goAway` message in `LiveServerMessageSerializer`

### 2. Robust Handling & API Update

- **Graceful Shutdown:** Implemented logic in `processModelResponses()`
to recognize `GoAway` signals and automatically close the session,
preventing zombie connections or further crashes.
- **Public API:** Added `goAwayHandler` to
`LiveAudioConversationConfig`.
- *Rationale:* While internal handling prevents the crash, apps often
need to inform the user that the session ended due to server maintenance
or timeouts. This handler exposes the `timeLeft` information to the
application layer.

## Usage Example

Apps can now handle server disconnections gracefully using the
`goAwayHandler`:

```kotlin
val config = LiveAudioConversationConfig.Builder()
  .setGoAwayHandler { goAway ->
    Log.i(TAG, "Server disconnecting in ${goAway.timeLeft?.inWholeSeconds} seconds")
    // Clean up resources, show UI notification, etc.
  }
  .build()

liveGenerativeModel.startAudioConversation(config)
```

## Testing

- unit tests
- Tested with [real
app](https://github.com/android/ai-samples/tree/prototype-ai-glasses)
and confirmed graceful handling of goAway messages (Published to local
Maven)
- Spotless formatting applied

## Related Issues

- Android SDK: #7648
- Flutter SDK: https://github.com/firebase/flutterfire/issues/17836

---------

firebase-firestore.message:
Fixed a race condition in test and remove null / nan related operations (#7741)

## Description

This PR introduces the following Beta API changes and related fixes:

* **Removed API Methods:** Removes the `isNan`, `isNotNan`, `isNull`,
and `isNotNull` pipeline string/number operations.
* **Changed `alias` Return Type:** Updates the `alias` method to now
return an `AliasedExpression` instead of `Selectable`.
* **Changelog Update:** Updates `CHANGELOG.md` to reflect these recent
Beta API changes.
* **Test Fixes:** Fixes build failures in `QueryToPipelineTest.java`
caused by the race condition.

firebase-installations.author: Vinay Guthal
firebase-installations.message:
Fix FIS ID duplication issue from backup data (#7096)

Currently, FIS apps are writing their data into the backup directory.
This causes an issue when a new installation retrieves data from the
backup, as it also picks up the previous FIS ID. This results in the FCM
server throwing an error, indicating that the FIS ID is already
associated with another instance. This PR fixes the issue for new apps
using FIS.
This PR also adds a function to the interop api which allows clearing of
fid cache. The implementation of the same is added in
FirebaseInstallations.java

Tested by creating two functions getDataFileBackup which stores it in
the backup directory and insertOrUpdatePersistedInstallationEntry which
the app data in the backup directory. So I call
insertOrUpdatePersistedInstallationEntry on the PersistedInstallation
object first and call getDataFileBackup and see that its back up
directory and then i call getDataFile() which would delete the
backupfile and return the nonbackupfile with that data. This was tested
by updating the PersistedInstallationTest.java . Also tested clearing
all this data with the clear function and it works

---------

Co-authored-by: Rodrigo Lazo <rlazo@users.noreply.github.com>
